    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-11-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-11-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="183"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d183">
                <head>183. Memorandum of Discussion at the 304th Meeting of the National Security
                    Council, Washington, November 15, 1956<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d183fn1"
                        >Source: Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Records. Top Secret. Drafted by Gleason on November
                        16.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-11-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 15, 1956</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Here follows a paragraph listing the participants at the meeting.]</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">1. Significant World Developments Affecting U.S. Security</hi>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of unrelated subjects.]</p>
                <p>Mr. [<persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen</persName>] <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                        >Dulles</persName> indicated that in Korea we had recently had some concern
                    after a jocular statement by President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> to our Ambassador to the effect that now that the U.S.
                    elections were over, he, <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>, was
                    planning to cause us a little trouble<note n="2" xml:id="d183fn2">The statement
                        by <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> to which <persName
                            corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> referred was made to Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_DWC1">Dowling</persName> and General <persName
                            corresp="#p_LGLL1">Lemnitzer</persName> on November 7, and was reported
                        in telegram 440 from Seoul, November 8. Telegram 440 is summarized in <ref
                            target="#d182fn5">footnote 5</ref>, <ref target="#d182">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                        </ref>
                    </note> The latest reports, however, indicate that this is a flash in the pan
                    and <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> does not seriously contemplate
                    meddling in North Korea.</p>
                <p>Displaying extreme irritation over President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName>’s behavior, the President indicated his belief that we must
                    make clear that we will not be blackmailed. He added that he was thoroughly fed
                    up with these “penny ante dictators”, and that it was high time to tell
                        <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> off.</p>
                <p>[Here follow discussion of unrelated subjects and the remaining agenda
                    items.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">S. Everett Gleason</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
